Load the Data

We will use two separate data sets for this homework.

  1. The first data set represent sightings of grizzly bears (Ursos arctos) in Alaska.
grizzly <- read.csv("data/bear-sightings.csv")
wolves <-read.csv("data/wolves_data/wolves_dataset.csv")

  1. The second data set is from Brandell, Ellen E (2021), Serological dataset and R code for: Patterns and processes of pathogen exposure in gray wolves across North America, Dryad, Dataset.

  2. Load the grizzly data and evaluate its structure.

glimpse(grizzly)

  1. Use the range of the latitude and longitude to build an appropriate bounding box for your map.
grizzly %>% 
  select(longitude, latitude) %>% 
  summary()
##    longitude         latitude    
##  Min.   :-166.2   Min.   :55.02  
##  1st Qu.:-154.2   1st Qu.:58.13  
##  Median :-151.0   Median :60.97  
##  Mean   :-149.1   Mean   :61.41  
##  3rd Qu.:-145.6   3rd Qu.:64.13  
##  Max.   :-131.3   Max.   :70.37
longitude <- c(-166.2,-131.3)
latitude <-c(55.02,70.37)
grizzlybbox <-make_bbox(longitude,latitude, f=0.05)
  1. Load a map from stamen in a terrain style projection and display the map.
map1<-get_map(grizzlybbox, maptype = "terrain", source = "stamen")
##  Map tiles by Stamen Design, under CC BY 3.0. Data by OpenStreetMap, under ODbL.
ggmap(map1)

  1. Build a final map that overlays the recorded observations of grizzly bears in Alaska.
ggmap(map1)+
  geom_point(data= grizzly, aes(longitude, latitude), alpha=0.75)+
  labs(title= "Grizzly Bears in Alaska", x= "Longitude", y = "Latitude")

  1. How many distinct wolf populations are included in this study? Make a new object that restricts the data to the wolf populations in the lower 48 US states.
tabyl(wolves$pop) #not alaska and canada

lower48 <-wolves %>% 
  filter(pop != "AK.PEN" & pop != "INT.AK" & pop != "SE.AK" & pop != "ONT" & pop != "BC" & pop!= "YUCH" & pop != "DENALI" & pop != "SS.NWT" & pop!= "ELLES" & pop!= "BAN.JAS" & pop!= "N.NWT") # removed anything not related to the lower 48 aka no alaska and canadian

coloring by pop

filling by pop

  geom_point(data=lower48, aes(long, lat, fill= pop))+
